A fan of true food, not a fan of this location. First time visitors should keep in mind that what you experience here is not the norm. There are much better locations (Like fairfax) out there. I can’t speak on the food because after being in the restaurant for over 30 mins (which probably counted towards the “90 min limit”) no one even offered me a glass of water. After being neglected, I told the bartender about my experience and how I usually go to fairfax, her response was “you should go to fairfax then” or something along those lines. I was famished so it didn’t resonate until after I walked away. The way the store is run, I wouldn’t be surprised it the food comes out cold and servers had attitude problems like the bartender did. But I can’t say for a fact because they never cared enough to greet me or attend to me.  P.s. I ended up coming to fairfax and it’s a night and day difference. All smiles and radiating positivity. I hope upper management takes notice.

I would like to preface this review by saying that I have only written one other Yelp review before. It was for a tailor who was able to alter a military uniform for me in a pinch and I was very appreciative, so I wanted to let others know of the great service. I do not typically feel moved to write reviews about negative experiences, but what happened to me at the Bethesda True Food Kitchen this past weekend was so unacceptable that it needs to be shared. A good friend of mine was visiting from out of town, so I decided to take her to True Food for dinner after having several delicious meals there in the past. I made a reservation for 7:15. We arrived to the restaurant at 7:22, upon which we had to wait in line to get checked in. We were checked in at 7:24 and told by the hostess that our table wasn't ready yet, so we would have to wait at the bar. This was not a problem, but I did nicely ask what time she anticipated our table being ready. She responded very rudely that the restaurant had a lot of reservations that night and she had "no idea" when the table would be ready. I was taken aback by this but did not wish to press the issue, so we went to the bar and ordered a drink. At 7:45, we still hadn't been seated, so I went back over to the hostess stand to check on the status of our table. The hostess once again responded with hostility that the restaurant had a lot of reservations that evening and there was nothing she could do about the wait. She then proceeded to swipe through all of the reservations that night on her iPad to prove her point. At this point, I asked her if I could speak to the manager. The manager came over and I introduced myself and began to explain the situation. The manager barely even let me get a word out before she told me that since I came in at 7:24 for my 7:15 reservation, my table had been given away. She then asked me, "At what point did you think it was acceptable to call my hostess an a**hole?" WHAT?!?! I was sooo totally shocked by this accusation that I didn't even know what to say. I told the manager that I would never call someone that and that I was extremely offended that she would point-blank accuse me of this. I explained that I had very nicely asked the hostess for an update on the table, she responded the way that she did, and I had asked her to see the manager. After I was done, the manage told me that she had "let me go on for long enough" and that a table would be ready soon. I was so upset that I was shaking and I told her that I had no intention of staying for dinner or ever returning to this restaurant again. She responded, "I am sorry you feel that way", and that was that. We placed our unfinished drinks on the bar and left. I have never been so poorly treated in my life by someone (supposedly) in the hospitality industry or otherwise. It is a wonder to me that this woman was even able to get a job at a chain restaurant in Bethesda for the way she feels it is acceptable to treat customers. I hope that at the very least, this manager will be required to undergo training so that she can learn how to not only be a better employee, but a better human being. We were fortunately able to salvage the evening by enjoying a lovely meal at Terrain down the street. I won't be back to True Food Bethesda, and I suggest others stay away.

Never again will I darken the doors of True Food but maybe you'll feel differently.  Perhaps you enjoy being treated like dirt by the local teenage princess slumming as hostess and perhaps you like having your waitress disappear after taking your drink order, never to appear again.  Curious?  A detailed explanation is in order.  On our reservation we had requested a quiet table; instead, we were seated adjacent to a table with a baby.  The baby was seated in the isle between our tables, so close that the back of its highchair was touching our table.  I reminded the hostess that we'd requested a quiet table and asked her to relocate us. Instead, the local teenage princess had the gall to argue with me! and refuse to reseat us, saying there weren't any other tables available.  When I pointed out two empty tables near us she eventually capitulated but bypassed the adjacent tables and seated us at the other end of the space in what seemed to be the loudest part of the restaurant.  Retribution for daring to ask the local teenage princess to be reseated?  It sure seemed like it.  When, again, I asked why we couldn't be seated at one of the other open tables in quieter locations (from our vantage point we could see four open tables) we got a series of lame and conflicting excuses handed out to us in an imperious and patronizing tone as though she was doing us a favor to deign to speak to us.  In hindsight we should have walked out then.  We gave up, our middle aged will thwarted by the obvious superiority of the local teenage princess.  When our waitress arrived we were still fuming but had hopes that a nice glass of wine would cure our ills.  Order placed, we sat back and waited, and waited, and waited.  Nada.  10 minutes, 15 minutes, who knows?  Finally the manager arrived to inform us that our waitress had left because her shift was over and he would take our order!  Needless to say we recounted to him our experience with the local teenage princess and our desire for a quieter table so he immediately relocated us to a fifth empty table that we hadn't seen before.  (Dear reader, this means that there were at least five empty tables that the local teenage princess had refused to relocate us to.)  After all this, did the quality of the food make up for the indignities we suffered?  No, unequivocally no!  You cannot make up for outrageously terrible service with decent food.  In closing, it is worth noting that the manager offered us nothing in compensation for the terrible service.  Reader be warned, True Food should be renamed Truely Awful.
